  "summary": "Josephine discusses her grandfather's death and her desire to study ballet, a dream he had strongly opposed. She reveals that her Uncle Roger and Aunt Clementine are planning a secret departure from the country on Tuesday. Josephine suspects Roger’s departure is linked to his business in London and believes he may have embezzled money, noting that Roger expressed deep disappointment to his father on the day the grandfather died. Admitting to eavesdropping to find the truth, Josephine claims to have read love letters between Brenda and Lawrence and expresses her intention to act as a detective to solve her grandfather's murder.\n\nThe conversation is interrupted by the arrival of the grandfather's lawyer, Mr. Gaskill, and Inspector Taverner. A dispute arises regarding the location of the grandfather's will. Magda Leonidis suspects an \"evil woman upstairs\" has destroyed it, believing such a person would inherit everything in its absence. While Mr. Gaskill suggests the will was in a safe, Inspector Taverner reports that the bank has no record of the document, only securities. Philip suggests Roger or Edith might know its location, but Roger denies involvement, claiming his father intended to send the will to Mr. Gaston. Mr. Gaston confirms he drafted the final will in November of the previous year, which the grandfather had approved and signed, intending to send it to the bank. Roger adds that the grandfather had previously read the will aloud to the family.",
